### 9. Default color in panel doesn't match rendered color (Gluestack internal tokens)

**Root cause:** Gluestack components like Button apply colors via internal CSS class tokens (`bg-primary-500`). These aren't extractable from `node.props.className`, so the color pickers showed `#ffffff` / `#000000` as defaults even when the component rendered blue.

**Fix:** Use a `useEffect` in `DesignTab` to read `window.getComputedStyle()` from the live DOM element after each render, then convert `rgb(r,g,b)` ŌåÆ hex. Store in local state (`computedBgColor`, `computedTextColor`, `computedBorderColor`). Pass these as the default values to `ColorInput`.

**Rule:** Never hardcode `#ffffff` as the default for a color input. Always read the real computed style from the DOM. Transparent (`rgba(0,0,0,0)`) should fall back to `#ffffff`.

---

### 10. Inline text editing ŌĆö double-click on canvas

**Feature:** Double-clicking a `Text`, `Heading`, or any text-type node on the canvas activates **contentEditable directly on the rendered DOM element**. No floating textarea ŌĆö the user edits the actual node in place. Fonts, size, color, and layout remain identical to the design.

**Implementation:** `_canvas.tsx` tracks only `editingId`. On double-click, the handler walks up the DOM tree (then down into children as fallback) to find a node whose type is in `TEXT_NODE_TYPES`. It then:
1. Sets `el.contentEditable = "true"` and adds a blue `outline` to the element.
2. Stores the original `innerText` in `editingOrigText` ref.
3. Attaches `paste` handler (plain-text only, strips HTML) and `keydown` handler (Enter = commit, Escape = cancel).
4. Focuses the element and selects all text via `Selection` API.

The **capture overlay** gets `pointerEvents: 'none'` while `editingId` is set, so all pointer/keyboard events reach the contenteditable element. Clicking outside the element commits (detected via `onPointerDown` on the overlay, which is still handled because the click propagates to the canvas div).

**Commit:** Reads `el.innerText` (strips trailing newline), calls `patchProp(editingId, 'text', newText)`, removes `contentEditable` + styling.

**Cancel (Escape):** Restores `el.innerText` to original, removes `contentEditable` + styling, does NOT call `patchProp`.

**Rule:** NEVER use a floating `<textarea>` for inline editing ŌĆö it causes font mismatch and overlap issues. Always use contentEditable on the actual element.

---

### 11. Content section in right panel (text editing)

**Feature:** When a `Text`, `Heading`, or any `isTextNode` is selected, a "Content" section appears at the top of the Design panel. For `isContainer` nodes (e.g. `Box`) that have a `Text` or `Heading` child, the section edits the first such child's `text`. Edits via `patchProp(nodeId, 'text', value)`.

**Rule:** Use `patchProp(id, 'text', value)` not `patchProp(id, 'props.text', value)` ŌĆö the `text` field is at the node root level, not inside `props`. The BoxŌåÆText child pattern (primitive button) is fully supported.

---

### 19. Drop indicator direction ŌĆö vertical for row containers

**Root cause:** The drop indicator (blue line) was always rendered horizontally (`dropLineY` only), even when dragging over a horizontal container (`HStack` or `Box flex-row`). Users saw the insertion cue in the wrong axis.

**Fix:**
1. `isRowContainer(node)` helper in `_canvas.tsx` ŌĆö returns `true` for `HStack` type OR any node whose `className` contains `flex-row`.
2. `nearestGapH(clientX, container, children)` ŌĆö mirrors `nearestGap()` but calculates insertion position along the X axis (returns `lineX`).
3. `dropLineX` state in `_canvas.tsx` ŌĆö holds the horizontal pixel position for the vertical indicator line.
4. `onDragOver` now calls `nearestGapH + setDropLineX` for row containers and `nearestGap + setDropLineY` for column containers. Both states are always reset together (only one is active at a time).
5. `DropZoneLine` in `_overlay.tsx` accepts both `x` (vertical line) and `y` (horizontal line). When `x` is set, renders a `2px ├Ś height` vertical bar; when `y` is set, renders a `width ├Ś 2px` horizontal bar.

**Tests:** `DI-01`ŌĆō`DI-04` in `test-dnd.spec.ts`.

**Rule:** Any container whose `type === 'HStack'` or whose `className` contains `flex-row` is a row container ŌĆö the insertion indicator must be vertical. All other containers use the existing horizontal line.

---

### 13. Dimensions Panel ŌĆö Four H/W Modes (Hug / Fill / Screen / Fixed)

**Width modes:**
- **Hug** ŌåÆ `w-fit` (shrink to content)
- **Fill** ŌåÆ `w-full` (100% of parent ŌĆö works because block elements expand horizontally naturally)
- **Screen** ŌåÆ `w-screen` (100vw ŌĆö always resolves regardless of parent)
- **Fixed** ŌåÆ inline `style.width` in px/vh/vw (unit switcher: [px][vh][vw] buttons in the Position & Size section)

**Height modes:**
- **Hug** ŌåÆ `h-fit` (shrink to content)
- **Fill** ŌåÆ `flex-1` (grow to fill remaining space in flex parent ŌĆö **matches Figma Fill behaviour**)
- **Screen** ŌåÆ `h-screen` (100vh ŌĆö always resolves regardless of parent; use for hero, modal overlay, full-page sections)
- **Fixed** ŌåÆ inline `style.height` in px/vh/vw

**Why Fill is `flex-1` not `h-full`:**
`h-full` (height: 100%) only works when every ancestor has an explicit pixel/viewport height. `flex-1` works in any flex container (which all layout Boxes already are by default). This matches exactly how Figma's Fill works ŌĆö "give me the leftover space".

**Helpers defined near top of the Design panel render function (`_panel-right.tsx`):**
```tsx
const clearHMode      = (c: string) => removeTwToken(removeTwToken(c, 'h-'), 'flex-1');
const clearHModeTokens = (c: string) => removeTwToken(removeTwToken(removeTwToken(c, 'h-fit'), 'h-screen'), 'flex-1');
const clearWMode      = (c: string) => removeTwToken(c, 'w-');
const clearWModeTokens = (c: string) => removeTwToken(removeTwToken(removeTwToken(c, 'w-fit'), 'w-full'), 'w-screen');
```

- `clearHMode` ŌĆö used when switching H modes (removes ALL h-* + flex-1 so old mode doesn't persist)
- `clearHModeTokens` ŌĆö used when setting a fixed pixel/vh/vw size (only removes mode tokens, preserves arbitrary h-[N] classes)
- Same pattern for W axis.

**Hug / Fill / Screen does nothing when previously resized:**
Inline styles have higher CSS specificity than classes. When switching to any class-based mode, clear the inline style first:
```tsx
patchCls(`${clearHMode(cls)} flex-1`.trim());
patchStyle({ height: '', minHeight: '' }); // must clear inline style
```

**Fixed stays active after switching to Fill/Hug/Screen:**
When a pixel/vh/vw size is set (via input or drag handle), remove all mode tokens so the panel reflects Fixed mode:
- W input: `patchCls(clearWModeTokens(cls))`
- H input: `patchCls(clearHModeTokens(cls))`
- Canvas resize handles: also remove `flex-1` and `w-screen`/`h-screen` alongside `w-fit`/`h-fit`

**Rule:** Any time you add a class-based mode (`flex-1`, `h-screen`, `h-fit`, `w-full`, etc.) you MUST also clear the inline style. Any time you set a fixed pixel/vh/vw size, you MUST also remove all mode tokens from className.

