## ┬¦33 Abs Drag Hover ŌĆö Correct Effective Parent Resolution

**Root cause (two cases):**

**Case A:** Hovering over another absolute node (e.g. dragging abs-button1 over abs-button2). If button2 has a `Text` child, `hovIsContainer = true`. The code set `effectiveParentId = hovId` (button2), treating it as a drop container. When the cursor touched button2's top edge and briefly exited, `effectiveParentId` flipped to `null` (same as `currentParentId`), clearing the container highlight.

**Fix A:** After computing `hovIsContainer`, also check if the hovered node is itself `absolute`/`fixed`. If it is, skip the container path:
```typescript
const hovCls = (hovNode?.props as { className?: string })?.className ?? '';
const hovIsAbs = /\b(absolute|fixed)\b/.test(hovCls);
if (hovIsContainer && !hovIsAbs) {
  effectiveParentId = hovId; // flow container ŌåÆ valid drop target
} else {
  // leaf OR abs node ŌåÆ use its parent
}
```

**Case B:** Cursor moves over a `Text` child inside an abs `Box`. `Text` is not abs, so `hovIsAbs = false`. Resolving `leafParent = Box` returns the abs Box as parent ŌĆö same problem.

**Fix B:** In the `else` branch, walk up the ancestor chain until finding a non-absolute parent:
```typescript
let resolvedParent = findParentNode(pNodes, hovId);
while (resolvedParent?.id) {
  const pCls = (resolvedParent.props as { className?: string })?.className ?? '';
  if (/\b(absolute|fixed)\b/.test(pCls)) {
    resolvedParent = findParentNode(pNodes, resolvedParent.id); // keep walking up
  } else {
    break;
  }
}
effectiveParentId = resolvedParent?.id ?? null;
```

**Rule:** When resolving the effective drop parent for an absolute drag, always walk up past any absolute/fixed ancestors. An absolute node is a sibling in stacking space, never a drop container.

